"become an error in a future pool versions. Please note that, currently, `!"
"open=True` is the default; in a future version, the default for the "
"parameter will be changed to `!False`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/pool.rst:344
msgid ""
"In order to make sure that your code will keep working as expected in future "
"versions, please specify `!open=False` in the constructor and use an "
"explicit `!await pool.open()`::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/pool.rst:348
msgid ""
"pool = AsyncConnectionPool(..., open=False)\n"
"await pool.open()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/pool.rst:351
msgid "or use the pool context manager::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/pool.rst:353
msgid ""
"async with AsyncConnectionPool(..., open=False) as pool:\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/pool.rst:356
msgid ""
"Starting from psycopg_pool 3.2, opening an async pool in the constructor "
"raises a warning."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/pool.rst:361
msgid ""
"async with my_pool.connection() as conn:\n"
"    await conn.execute(...)\n"
"\n"
"# the connection is now back in the pool"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/pool.rst:373
msgid ""
"The pool can be also used as an async context manager, in which case it will "
"be opened (if necessary) on entering the block and closed on exiting it:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/pool.rst:377
msgid ""
"async with AsyncConnectionPool(...) as pool:\n"
"    # code using the pool"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/pool.rst:382
msgid "All the other constructor parameters are the same of `!ConnectionPool`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/pool.rst:396
msgid "Null connection pools"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/pool.rst:400
msgid ""
"The `NullConnectionPool` is a `ConnectionPool` subclass which doesn't create "
"connections preemptively and doesn't keep unused connections in its state. "
"See :ref:`null-pool` for further details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/pool.rst:404
msgid ""
"The interface of the object is entirely compatible with its parent class. "
"Its behaviour is similar, with the following differences:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/pool.rst:409
msgid ""
"All the other constructor parameters are the same as in `ConnectionPool`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/pool.rst:411
msgid "Always 0, cannot be changed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/pool.rst:414
msgid ""
"If None or 0, create a new connection at every request, without a maximum. "
"If greater than 0, don't create more than `!max_size` connections and queue "
"the waiting clients."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/pool.rst:419
msgid ""
"It is only called when there are waiting clients in the queue, before giving "
"them a connection already open. If no client is waiting, the connection is "
"closed and discarded without a fuss."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/pool.rst:425
msgid "Ignored, as null pools don't leave idle connections sitting around."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg_pool/null_pool.py:docstring
#: of psycopg_pool.null_pool.NullConnectionPool.wait:1
msgid "Create a connection for test."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg_pool/null_pool.py:docstring
#: of psycopg_pool.null_pool.NullConnectionPool.wait:3
msgid ""
"Calling this function will verify that the connectivity with the database "
"works as expected. However the connection will not be stored in the pool."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg_pool/null_pool.py:docstring
#: of psycopg_pool.null_pool.NullConnectionPool.resize:3
msgid "Only *max_size* can be changed; *min_size* must remain 0."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg_pool/null_pool.py:docstring
#: of psycopg_pool.null_pool.NullConnectionPool.check:1
msgid "No-op, as the pool doesn't have connections in its state."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/pool.rst:433
msgid ""
"The `AsyncNullConnectionPool` is, similarly, an `AsyncConnectionPool` "
"subclass with the same behaviour of the `NullConnectionPool`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/pool.rst:438
msgid ""
"The interface is the same of its parent class `AsyncConnectionPool`. The "
"behaviour is different in the same way described for `NullConnectionPool`."
